Will technology save the world?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout his dissertation, you notice that Meino Smit questions the sustainabi
lity of electronics and a switch to renewable energy in a 
\begin_inset Quotes pld
\end_inset

business-as-usual
\begin_inset Quotes prd
\end_inset

 scenario.
 For me, coming from the IT sector, that was a bitter pill to swallow.
 Although what is discussed here is not directly related to the real subject
 of this in-depth piece of work, due to my background, I would like share
 it with you.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
External costs of electronics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Electronics is a strange thing.
 We can't imagine life without them, and this dependence has crept into
 our lives awfully fast.
 Electronics has also become prominent in agriculture in a short period
 of time.
 Drones to plant crops, vertical farming, sensors galore,
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

\SpecialChar ldots

\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

.
 You can't think of anything or electronics has a foot in the door or even
 more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More capital is required for the production of electronics than during their
 use.
 Production is also where most of the waste is generated, not the disposal
 of the electronic devices.
 This indicates that recycling of electronic equipment is useful but will
 not greatly reduce the footprint.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During usable lifetime of electronics, a variety of other electronics is
 also needed to transport (data communication networks such as 4G, WiFi,
 fiber optics,
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

\SpecialChar ldots
), process (computing centers) and store (storage centers) the data that
 is generated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at costs, the following can be noted:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the large energy consumption in production,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the raw materials used:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
the mining and extraction of various crucial raw materials is burdensome,
 both in energy and social costs:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
use of fracking
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
toxic and radioactive waste
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
blood metals
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
some needed metals are only obtained as byproduct of other raw materials,
 which does not allow for a rapid response to fluctuations in demand,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the high dependence on rare earths with exotic names like neodymium, dysprosium
 or europium also has geopolitical consequences.
 85% of rare earths today come from China! That gives one country enormous
 control over its global supply,
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
production of the chips themselves is a toxic process requiring ultra pure
 water,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
processing the waste,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the use of an electronic device, as mentioned above, requires a plethora
 of other electronic devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The costs and benefits of electronics are disproportionately distributed.
 Those who take pleasure in electronics are totally unaffected by its costs
 in terms of social exploitation, toxic waste, land loss,
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

\SpecialChar ldots

\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are continuous improvements in the efficiency of production and of
 the equipment itself.
 But this is mostly offset by the ever-increasing consumption of electronic
 equipment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not the intention to condemn electronics.
 But it is important to be conscious of its impact.
 So what does this entail ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
First think carefully whether you really need the electronics.
 Marketing is very good at talking you into buying a new or more complex
 appliance because of features you don't really need.
 Is it so important that your refrigerator automatically orders milk?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When you buy, first look for a valid appliance on the secondhand market.
 This avoids the burdensome manufacturing process and it's waste.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Make your electronics last as long as possible.
 Electronic equipment has a very short life cycle.
 Since much of the cost is in manufacturing, a longer life cycle is a good
 way to reduce its footprint.
 This also means that it is best not to purchase a more energy friendly
 appliance because in most cases this is more taxing than continuing to
 use the old one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Whenever possible, make use of wires.
 Wifi, GSM and other wireless communications have a higher footprint than
 
\begin_inset Quotes pld
\end_inset

good old
\begin_inset Quotes prd
\end_inset

 network cables or landline phones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Buy electronic devices that you can repair.
 Usually electronic devices are repaired by replacing entire circuit boards.
 The smaller the circuit boards that are replaced, the less impact the repair
 will have.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Renewable energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Meino Smit is not convinced that the current evolution of energy use allows
 for the phasing out of fossil fuels in favor of renewable energy.
 This has not so much to do with the technology itself, but rather from
 an assessment of the amount of raw materials needed to complete the transformat
ion and how quickly they need to be available.
 This is going to have an impact on 
\begin_inset Quotes pld
\end_inset

Business as usual
\begin_inset Quotes prd
\end_inset

 scenarios.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rare earths also play an important role in renewable energy.
 Not only because of the electronics used, but also because these metals,
 for example, greatly increase the efficiency of magnets or are needed in
 solar cells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most forms of renewable energy are less efficient than fossil fuels.
 In figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:eroei-energiebronnen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 you can find the minimum and maximum EROEI of a number of energy sources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The EROEI of renewable fuels is linked to that of fossil fuels because even
 today the latter are consumed to make the infrastructure of the former
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Currently, 85% of our energy needs are met by burning fuels.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, if the EROEI of fossil fuels decreases, the EROEI of renewable
 fuels will also decrease.
 Since the easier to extract fossil fuels are consumed first, more energy
 must be used in the future to extract the same amount of energy.
 In the beginning, the EROEI for natural gas was 100:1.
 Now, however, it has dropped to 10:1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is assumed that an EROEI of 3:1 to 5:1 is needed for an energy source
 to have a positive energy balance.
 This is because the storage, conversion, transportation and distribution
 also require a great deal of energy.
\end_layout

